The  definitive  report on the 'happenings',  non-happenings,  and 
especially certain non-arrivals (hi James!)

Is it really now three weeks after the event? It is only now, that 
the last of the Jammie Dodgers are being eaten,  (YES NOW!) (kinda 
unusual  approach  to  breakfast on a Sunday  morning?)  and  this 
report is being written at last..

These  are  the views and observations of the main  man  involved, 
CiH..  There  are other accounts of these desperate times,  one or 
two of these may even be seen in this issue of Maggie as well, and 
indeed,  this  report  is  'embedded' with the full  text  of  the 
realtime  article to add to your reading pleasure,  but to be able 
to consider the whole thing from start to finish, then start right 
here..

No, not there -  Here!!
(Cah, just can't get quality readers these days!)

New Shell..
We  go  back some time before the start of  this,  several  issues 
ago..  I've always wanted a specific Falcon enhanced Maggie shell, 
almost  since the issue 12 fixes to get the Delta Force  model  to 
run on the '030.. Initial ideas went to an upgrade to the existing 
code,  say  a  nice  256 colour min menu piccy,  and four  channel 
MODfile music instead of Big Alec, or total silence in the case of 
the Falcon..  According to Felice,  someone did have a go at doing 
this,  but  due to pressure on their time,  was unable to get very 
far..  Another  possible  avenue was peeked into,  with the  shell 
program  that RiCH Davey was developing for his  magazine,  Falcon 
Update  Digital,  but  this  was not really quite what we  had  in 
mind..  

The next logical step, had to be to approach someone reliable that 
we  knew,  who  could do a good job if we asked them..  Enter Leon 
O'Reilly and his hatful of pseudonyms..

I  approached  him towards the end of last year with the  idea  of 
doing a Falcon specific Maggie, and he said, yes, he would like to 
do that..  Some thoughts of mine were clarified into written form, 
and  things started in earnest..  Leon had some ideas of his  own, 
and  a free hand to carry them out with..  The new Maggie would be 
started entirely from scratch, although with certain good features 
of  the Delta Force shell hopefully kept in,  which was really the 
way it should have been from the start..

Anniversaries..
Maggie reached its third birthday very shortly after the 'rebirth' 
issue 11 was released..  We were not really conscious of that fact 
though,  just being pleased to make it back into circulation.. The 
first  outburst  of  temporal  awareness  came  with  the   fourth 
anniversary  issue,  in a slightly surprised,  "So here we are yet 
again?" type of editorial..  Around this time, we decided it would 
be really neat to have some sort of celebration of the fifth year, 
which was going to originally be issue 17.. 

At  the  end of last year,  some firmer decisions were  made,  the 
fifth anniversary issue would now be issue 18, which had an August 
release  date  pencilled  in for it..  Realising that  the  actual 
anniversary  date was in very early June,  but also realising that 
this  date  fell inbetween the normal release dates,  which  would 
have  left  us  with either a very late 'spring'  issue  (with  no 
Falcon shell!), or a very rushed and poor quality effort to try to 
make  the June 'deadline'..  We got around the problem by deciding 
on  a totally new date a long time in advance,  which was just  as 
well really..

A preliminary invitation thing was issued to a number of  selected 
people, some of them even eventually turned up..

The shell was making good progress,  the original modest 'upgrade' 
turning  into a new and exciting creation,  and in good time,  the 
first  preview,  of  the  text  displayer  was  shown..  This  was 
essentially  what  there  is  today,  but with  the  nice  rastery 
background  removed  in the final version as rasters  and  Falcons 
don't go together very well at all.. 

Time skims on,  summer approaches, final invitations are sent out, 
a further preview is seen,  and shown to a select few,  this time, 
the  first inklings of the main menu system are seen as well..  It 
all  looks  so  good..  The  usual jobs of gathering  in  all  the 
textfiles  from promised contributors,  and writing what is due to 
done  by yourself are done..  The replies to the invitations start 
to trickle in, a mixed bag, with several 'no's for various reasons 
mixed  in with the positive ones..  The one thing that this  event 
could have done with, were a few more people, but not too many, as 
events turned out, could we have coped, frankly, I doubt it..
  
By  the time of the final ten days in August,  the phone lines are 
burning up daily over last minute changes and hassles,  it is like 
trying  to  nail  a  jelly to the floor,  but  a  plan  is  pieced 
together.. 

The very last few days are spent in finishing touches to the  mag, 
the  very  last  articles,  are  done,  and the first  attempt  at 
compiling  the  regular  (IE Delta Force) version  of  Maggie  are 
done..  This  saves us a heck of a lot of time later on..  The one 
slight  problem is that an ASCII graphic of a birthday cake  drawn 
by Mike Noyce,  and intended for the bottom 'blank' menu bar, does 
not translate very well at all to the Maggie character set.. After 
some  fiddling  aropund,  this  is  ditched,  and some  cheap  and 
cheerful ASCII large text is put there instead..  

Thursday,  the  flat  is cleaned by me,  in a mad  spring-cleaning 
frenzy..  I'm  sure  no-one wants to sleep on a floor  with  three 
months of debris on it!! I also go shopping, and load a trolley up 
with  gallons  of coke,  and lots of junk food..  Pausing only  to 
complain about declining educational standards to the woman in the 
queue  next  to  me  (or  whatever  else  people  talk  about   in 
supermarket  queues),  I  get  home..  A large amount of junk  and 
furniture  re-arranging  follows to make the best  of  the  rather 
small  amount of space there is..  In the suddenly rather spacious 
(for one person) lounge, I settle down to write the editorial, the 
very last text,  apart from the READ.ME file to be done on the day 
itself..

All ready now, just have to await the hordes tomorrow..

Friday 18th August..
The  day it all begins,  well another thing you may like to  know, 
was that I was busy at work on some kind of training course  where 
you  had to banter,  role-play and have yourself videoed 'doing  a 
General  Patton'  to  various  kinds  of  receptive,   or  hostile 
audiences,  good  training  for facing the next forty eight  hours 
maybe??

Five thirty-ish, I get home, the first arrival is Leon, due at the 
not  unreasonable hour of 6.30pm,  time to sit down,  get changed, 
let  the dust of the day settle down a bit you may think..  Not  a 
chance,  the  phone is ringing even as I struggle the key into the 
front door lock..  It is Leon,  who having encountered a fortunate 
conjunction  of trains in the Birmingham New Street star  cluster, 
was  able to make it to sunny Northampton a whole  hour  earlier.. 
Yippee, time to go..

Another problem was the fact that the usually tedious Rushden rush 
hour  traffic  was  moving even slower than  usual,  with  several 
police  cars blocking off key areas..  (This turned out to be  the 
aftermath of the fatal accident referred to by Felice in the real-
time text a bit later on..) 

Nevertheless, with the sun low in the western sky, I drive towards 
Northampton  at  demon-possessed speed,  arriving at  the  railway 
station,  somewhere  in the region of the half-hour I had promised 
Leon  on  the  phone..  I park,  and find Leon,  another  pleasant 
surprise is the presence of his sister Natasha (Ripley of the Res. 
Gods)..  Leon is wearing a hilarious baseball cap,  which is a bit 
too  big for him,  and has the effect of trimming a half-decade or 
more  off his real age..  He apparently managed to get a half-fare 
for  the  train  with the aid of this dubious  hat!!  He  did  not 
succeed  in removing this humourous headgear until very  late  the 
next day!?!

We get back home, having now got a whole hour to myself before the 
next  pick-up,  which  is RiCH Davey and VoGue (Rich and John)  at 
8.15pm..  I  introduce  Leon  to the fridge,  and my  Falcon  very 
quickly  and in roughly that order,  and he sets to work  straight 
away  on  the  '030  edition of Maggie  18..  This  is  his  first 
encounter with TOS 4.01 (A close encounter of the wonky kind!) and 
immediately,  lots  of things need doing to get it to run properly 
on  the subtly different environment that is my Falcon..  However, 
he does start getting results quickly, so I am at last able to see 
the new shell and text displayer in all its fully working  glory.. 
Overcome with this,  I rush off to ring up a bemused Slimer of DBA 
mag  over  in Holland,  who wonders if I am on drugs owing to  the 
delerious style of conversation I am using.. "Not Yet!" I reply..

The  next pick up looms closer,  for this one,  I am expecting the 
arrival of Richard (Felice) around 7.30pm,  and he does,  so it is 
off  back  to  town in his car,  which seems to take him  aback  a 
little,  in  spite of the fact this had been discussed  previously 
with him..  Some more dual carriageway type traversing later,  and 
we  pull up outside the looming 'Fuhrerbunker' style mass  of  the 
Greyfriars  Bus Station in Northampton..  We have but a few  scant 
minutes  to  wait,  as a more or less on time coach  from  Bristol 
arrives..  Straining  to catch sight of RiCH and John as they pile 
off  the  bus..  We all file back to Felice's car for the  journey 
home..

One little detour to the house of a friend who is kindly  donating 
the  use  of his STe,  Atari colour monitor,  and his 15 inch SVGA 
monitor..  These  are  loaded in the boot by our troops  who  take 
things  fairly  carefully an account of (A) they have just  had  a 
long  tiring coach journey,  and (B) Nathan,  whose gear it indeed 
is,  is  quite  useful with a length of bamboo stick,  in a  Bruce 
Lee/Jackie Chan sort of way!

We get back, we unload both people and computer gear into a lounge 
area that is rapidly filling up..  As well as all the other stuff, 
everyone else thus far has brought with them,  their fair share of 
bags,  sleeping  bags,  and  odds and sods have come too,  so it is 
starting  to  get problematic where to put your feet  if  you  are 
trying to get across the room.. Also kindly donated to the weekend 
is RiCH's laptop PC (Commodore 286 model!) This is to be the  home 
and  sanctuary of the realtime article,  with VoGue effectively in 
charge of this.. 

It is goodbye from me again,  as I set off yet again, this time in 
my  own car,  to pick up the final two arrivals for this  evening, 
namely Kev and Tat..

The  journey  down is remarkably similar to all  the  others  I've 
done,  apart from the fact that it is now dark, and the Pink Floyd 
tape in the old car stereo ('Animals') is somewhat nearer the  end 
than  before  ..  Kev  and Tat are due to  arrive  at  Northampton 
Railway station at 9.30pm.. I am told to look out for an Endsleigh 
football  shirt  getting off the train  (presumably  with  someone 
inside  of  it,  a disembodied footy shirt on its own would  be  a 
'tat' alarming methinks!?!?)

The  'choo-choo'  arrives from 'Oop-T'North' and two  very  scarey 
people  approach..  Kev ('SH3' of The Res..  Gods) has bought some 
dodgy hair from a street trader,  especially for the occasion.. It 
is  sadistically yellow,  sort of nuclear weapons flash in texture 
with approximately the same sort of long term damage to your  eyes 
afterwards.. Tat looks almost human.. Pausing briefly to point out 
a  very  sad plaque which commemorated Northampton  Station  being 
made  into  a  cattle-shed construction sometime in  1987,  we  go 
home..

With the addition of two more people, and their gear and bags, the 
space  situation  can be described as 'cosy',  extremely cosy,  in 
fact..  With people tending to dump their stuff any old how, it is 
a  tight spot we are all in,  and not a clue between us how to get 
out of it..

About  this  time,  some  fumbling around for a  spare  powerpoint 
managed  to see the Laptop burst into life,  and the start of  the 
realtime article, at about this point.. 

